        "text": "Watched a 35mm screening of the film today.\n\nRemember my family having it on VHS growing up, but I don't remember ever seeing it.\n\nAnthony Hopkins really shines in his role. Emma Thompson is good as always. It is like a lowkey version of The Bridges of Madison County. I really liked it. Such a beautiful and well acted film. Always nice to see Christopher Reeves in a non-Superman role too.\n\nWell acted but I admit a bit slow for me to indulge in repeated viewings.\n\nThat said, this scene always hurts to watch, between the longing, desire, and frankly, the pain of the self-imposed blue balling as Steven upholds his incredible pride, noble work ethic, and unshakeable loyalty.\n\nShe tries so hard. And I anytime I see this flick I always think of that \"what if things went just a BIT differently\" over and over.\n\nIt's a movie that's manages to deal with an incredible number of themes and still at its heart be a love story.\n\nIt's the final part of an informal trilogy in Merchant-Ivory's catalogue - Room With A View & Howard's End being the first two - and yes I know they're probably seen as prettty old hat & problematic by the young'uns but the whole late Victorian-Post-WW2 decline of the aristocracy & social changes period interests me, and as with the excellent character acting is also why I'm a closest Downton fan too."
